Project Description¶

Background and Context¶

Businesses like banks that provide service have to worry about the problem of 'Churn' i.e. customers leaving and joining another service provider. It is important to understand which aspects of the service influence a customer's decision in this regard. Management can concentrate efforts on the improvement of service, keeping in mind these priorities.

Objective¶

Given a Bank customer, build a neural network-based classifier that can determine whether they will leave or not in the next 6 months.

Data Description¶

The case study is from an open-source dataset from Kaggle. The dataset contains 10,000 sample points with 14 distinct features such as CustomerId, CreditScore, Geography, Gender, Age, Tenure, Balance, etc.

Data Dictionary¶

  • RowNumber: Row number
  • CustomerId: Unique identification key for different customers
  • Surname: Surname of the customer
  • Credit Score: A credit score is a measure of an individual's ability to pay back the borrowed amount. It is the numerical representation of their creditworthiness. A credit score is a 3-digit number that falls in the range of 300-900, 900 being the highest.
  • Geography: The country to which the customer belongs
  • Gender: The gender of the customer
  • Age: Age of the customer
  • Tenure: The period of time a customer has been associated with the bank
  • Balance: The account balance (the amount of money deposited in the bank account) of the customer.
  • NumOfProducts: How many accounts, bank account affiliated products the person has.
  • HasCrCard: Does the customer have a credit card through the bank?
  • IsActiveMember: Subjective, but for the concept
  • EstimatedSalary: Estimated salary of the customer
  • Exited: Did they leave the bank after all?

# Function to create boxplot and histogram for any input numerical variable
# This function takes the numerical column as the input and returns the boxplots 
# and histograms for the variable.

def histogram_boxplot(feature, figsize=(15,10), bins = None):
    """ Boxplot and histogram combined
    feature: 1-d feature array
    figsize: size of fig (default (9,8))
    bins: number of bins (default None / auto)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(nrows = 2, # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
                                           sharex = True, # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
                                           gridspec_kw = {"height_ratios": (.25, .75)}, 
                                           figsize = figsize 
                                           ) # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color='violet') # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(feature, kde=F, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins,palette="winter") if bins else sns.histplot(feature, kde=False, ax=ax_hist2) # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(np.mean(feature), color='green', linestyle='--') # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(np.median(feature), color='black', linestyle='-') # Add median to the histogram

#Finding percentage of outliers, in each column of the data, using IQR
num_cols = ['CreditScore','Age','Balance','EstimatedSalary']
Q1 = dataCC[num_cols].quantile(0.25) #25th percentile           
Q3 = dataCC[num_cols].quantile(0.75) #75th percentile

#Inter Quantile Range (75th perentile - 25th percentile) 
IQR = Q3 - Q1                          

#Finding lower and upper bounds based on IQR. All values outside these bounds are considered outliers
lower=Q1-1.5*IQR                        
upper=Q3+1.5*IQR

#Function to plot barchart with percentage for categorical variables

def perc_on_bar(feature):
    '''
    plot
    feature: categorical feature
    the function won't work if a column is passed in hue parameter
    '''
    #Creating a countplot for the feature
    sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(15,7)})
    ax=sns.countplot(x=feature, data=dataCC)
    
    total = len(feature) # length of the column
    for p in ax.patches:
        percentage = '{:.1f}%'.format(100 * p.get_height()/total) # percentage of each class of the category
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2 - 0.25 # width of the plot
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()           # hieght of the plot
        ax.annotate(percentage, (x, y), size = 14) # annotate the percantage 
        
    plt.show() # show the plot

#Function to get count plot with hue, that shows % among each class
#Shows crosstab again for better readability and to show % within class and different classes altogether
def perc_on_bar_with_hue(x):
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(dataCC[x],dataCC['Exited'],margins=True)
    print(tab1)
    print('-'*80)    
    df1 = dataCC.groupby(x)['Exited'].value_counts(normalize=True)
    df1 = df1.mul(100)
    df1 = df1.rename('percent').reset_index()

    g = sns.catplot(x=x,y='percent',hue='Exited',kind='bar',data=df1,aspect=2.0)
    g.ax.set_ylim(0,100)    

    for p in g.ax.patches:
        #print(p)
        height = p.get_height()        
        if np.isnan(height):
            height = 0
        txt = str(round(height,2)) + '%'
        txt_x = p.get_x() 
        txt_y = height
        g.ax.text(txt_x,txt_y,txt)

Insights based on EDA¶

Key meaningful observations on the relationship between variables¶
  • Geography seems to have an impact on exited customer %. Exited % is higher for Germany, compared to other 2 locations.
  • Gender seems to have an impact on exited customer %. Exited % is higher in Females.
  • Tenure period does not seem to have an impact on Exited %. Exited Vs Non-exited customers % seem to be same across different tenures.
  • Number of Products seem to have an impact on Exited %. Exited % is high for customers having Number of Products 3 and 4.
  • HasCrCard does not seem to have an impact on Exited %. Exited Vs Non-exited customers % seem to be same across customers with CC and customers without CC.
  • % of Exited customers seem to be more when IsActiveMember flag is 0. This makes sense, when a member is active, chances are that the member is going to keep using bank services.
  • Bivariate anaysis shows that target variable (Exited) is not much impacted by CreditScore and EstimatedSalary. Avg Credit Score slightly lower for Exited customers, which makes sense, customers with less credit score may not be getting more services from bank and hence there is possibility for them to leave. Avg Estimated Salary bit high for Exited customers.
  • Age slightly more for customers who left the bank services compared to customers who continue to use bank services.
  • 25th percentile and 50th percentile for Balance seem to be more for customers who left the bank services compared to customers who continue to use bank services. Avg Balance also shows bit high for Exited customers.
  • From heatmap bivariate analysis, Age shows a small positive correlation with target variable Exited.
  • From heatmap bivariate analysis, Balance shows a small -ve correlation with NumberOfProducts.
  • From heatmap bivariate analysis, Balance also shows a very small positive correlation with target variable Exited.
  • From heatmap bivariate analysis, IsActiveMember shows a small -ve correlation with target variable Exited.

Should we do PCA??

  • PCA can be used to reduce dimensions, if the dataset has too many variables and there is a possibility of 'curse of dimensionality'
  • PCA can also be used to remove multicollinearity to make the variables independent
  • In the given dataset, from pairplot and heatmap, we have seen that, there are no strong correlation between variables
  • And there are only 11 variables in this given dataset, after removing ID columns
  • Considering these points, I believe, we do not need to do PCA for dimensionality reduction
Data Pre-processing¶
  • RowNumber column removed since that is just an ID column and not going to add value to the model
  • CustomerId column removed since that is just an ID column and not going to add value to the model
  • Surname column removed since that is just customer name and not going to have any value to the model
  • Missing (null) value check is done on all columns and no nulls are present in the dataset
  • Outliers are present in Age and CreditScore, they were explained in the univariate analysis .Since those values are not standing out from the rest of the data, they are not removed
  • Target variable (Exited) is a categorical column and need to be converted to category before building the model
  • None of the columns in this dataset shows a very strong correlation with the target variable, so decided to keep all features for model building
  • All features are in different scales, so need to scale or normalize these features before model building.
  • Categorical column need to be one-hot encoded before model building.

Model Building¶
Model performance evaluation criterion¶
  • The objective is to find out if a customer is going to leave bank services or not (churn prediction). Because customers leaving bank services would lead bank to loss, so the bank wants to analyze the data of customers and identify the customers who will leave their services.
Here are the wrong predictions that the model can make¶
  • Predicting a customer will leave bank services and the customer does not leave
  • Predicting a customer will NOT leave bank services and the customer leaves
Which prediction is more important¶
  • In the first scenario, the model predicts customer will leave bank services, so the bank takes effort to retain them, which causes the bank more resources and money
  • In the second scenario, the model predicts customer will NOT leave bank services, so the bank is not going to take any effort to retain those customers, but in real world scenario the customer leaves the serives, which causes the bank huge loss
Which is the right metric for model evaluation¶
  • The first wrong prediction type is FP (False Positive) and the second wrong prediction type is FN(False Negative)
  • Since the bank wants to avoid losses due to customers leaving bank services, we need to focus on reducing the false negatives, recall is the right metric in this case, greater the Recall lesser the chances of false negatives
  • We will focus more on Recall, but also keep an eye on precision, which is the metric if our focus is on reducing false positives, in this case reducing the resources
How to interpret confusion matrix for the given problem¶

True Positives:

  • Reality: A customer leaves bank services
  • Model predicted: The customer will leave bank services
  • Outcome: The model is good

True Negatives:

  • Reality: A customer does not leave bank services
  • Model predicted: The customer will NOT leave bank services
  • Outcome: The model is good

False Positives:

  • Reality: A customer does not leave bank services
  • Model predicted: The customer will leave bank services
  • Outcome: Bank will be spending more on resources trying to reatin the customers who will not leave bank services

False Negatives:

  • Reality: A customer leaves bank services
  • Model predicted: The customer will NOT leave bank services
  • Outcome: Bank will face a huge loss, since they will not focus on retaining the potential customers who will leave bank services
Model Evaluation¶
  • It is recommended to split the dataset into training,evaluation and testing and fit the model on training set, perform hyper parameter tuning on evaluation set and after finding the right set of parameters check if the model is underfit, overfit or right fit on the test set
  • Here validation_split is used when fitting the model, which will split data in training set again into train and validation sets.
  • Initially dataset is split into train (80% -> 8000 records) and test (20% -> 2000 records). Then validation_split = 0.2 will split training set into train (80% of 80000 -> 6400 records) and validation (20% of 8000 -> 1600 records).
  • Validation set is used to calculate the accuracy at the end of each epoch
  • Once all epochs are complete and when the model is ready for final evaluation, test set is used to find the testing accuracy.

Function to produce confusion matrix in a more readable format

In [89]:
def make_confusion_matrix(cf,
                          group_names=None,
                          categories='auto',
                          count=True,
                          percent=True,
                          cbar=True,
                          xyticks=True,
                          xyplotlabels=True,
                          sum_stats=True,
                          figsize=None,
                          cmap='Blues',
                          title=None):
    '''
    This function will make a pretty plot of an sklearn Confusion Matrix cm using a Seaborn heatmap visualization.
    Arguments
    '''


    # CODE TO GENERATE TEXT INSIDE EACH SQUARE
    blanks = ['' for i in range(cf.size)]

    if group_names and len(group_names)==cf.size:
        group_labels = ["{}\n".format(value) for value in group_names]
    else:
        group_labels = blanks

    if count:
        group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}\n".format(value) for value in cf.flatten()]
    else:
        group_counts = blanks

    if percent:
        group_percentages = ["{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in cf.flatten()/np.sum(cf)]
    else:
        group_percentages = blanks

    box_labels = [f"{v1}{v2}{v3}".strip() for v1, v2, v3 in zip(group_labels,group_counts,group_percentages)]
    box_labels = np.asarray(box_labels).reshape(cf.shape[0],cf.shape[1])


    # CODE TO GENERATE SUMMARY STATISTICS & TEXT FOR SUMMARY STATS
    if sum_stats:
        #Accuracy is sum of diagonal divided by total observations
        accuracy  = np.trace(cf) / float(np.sum(cf))

        #if it is a binary confusion matrix, show some more stats
        if len(cf)==2:
            #Metrics for Binary Confusion Matrices
            precision = cf[1,1] / sum(cf[:,1])
            recall    = cf[1,1] / sum(cf[1,:])
            f1_score  = 2*precision*recall / (precision + recall)
            stats_text = "\n\nAccuracy={:0.3f}\nPrecision={:0.3f}\nRecall={:0.3f}\nF1 Score={:0.3f}".format(
                accuracy,precision,recall,f1_score)
        else:
            stats_text = "\n\nAccuracy={:0.3f}".format(accuracy)
    else:
        stats_text = ""


    # SET FIGURE PARAMETERS ACCORDING TO OTHER ARGUMENTS
    if figsize==None:
        #Get default figure size if not set
        figsize = plt.rcParams.get('figure.figsize')

    if xyticks==False:
        #Do not show categories if xyticks is False
        categories=False


    # MAKE THE HEATMAP VISUALIZATION
    plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
    sns.heatmap(cf,annot=box_labels,fmt="",cmap=cmap,cbar=cbar,xticklabels=categories,yticklabels=categories)

    if xyplotlabels:
        plt.ylabel('True label')
        plt.xlabel('Predicted label' + stats_text)
    else:
        plt.xlabel(stats_text)
    
    if title:
        plt.title(title)

Building NN model¶

Model-1

  • We will use a simple NN made of 4 fully-connected layers with ReLu activation. The NN takes a vector of length 11 as input. This represents 11 input columns from the dataset. The final layer will output a probability distribution (sigmoid activation function) and classify either as not Exited (0) or Exited (1).
  • A dropout step is included to prevent overfitting.

ROC-AUC and Precision-Recall curves

  • ROC Curves summarize the trade-off between the true positive rate and false positive rate for a predictive model using different probability thresholds
  • Precision-Recall curves summarize the trade-off between the true positive rate and the positive predictive value for a predictive model using different probability thresholds
  • ROC curves are appropriate when the observations are balanced between each class, whereas precision-recall curves are appropriate for imbalanced datasets
  • Now we are going to see both to find out the threshold values

ROC-AUC

  • ROC curve is a plot of the false positive rate (x-axis) versus the true positive rate (y-axis) for a number of different candidate threshold values between 0.0 and 1.0
  • True Positive Rate (Sensitivity) = True Positives / (True Positives + False Negatives)
  • False Positive Rate (1 - Specificity) = False Positives / (False Positives + True Negatives)
  • The area under the curve (AUC) can be used as a summary of the model performance
  • Smaller values on the x-axis of the plot indicate lower false positives and higher true negatives
  • Larger values on the y-axis of the plot indicate higher true positives and lower false negatives
  • A model with no skill is represented at the point (0.5, 0.5). A model with no skill at each threshold is represented by a diagonal line from the bottom left of the plot to the top right and has an AUC of 0.5
  • A model with perfect skill is represented at a point (0,1). A model with perfect skill is represented by a line that travels from the bottom left of the plot to the top left and then across the top to the top right
  • roc_auc_score gives AUC score between 0 and 1, for no skill and perfect skill respectively
  • The Geometric Mean or G-Mean is a metric for imbalanced classification that, if optimized, will seek a balance between the sensitivity and the specificity
  • G-Mean = sqrt(Sensitivity * Specificity)

#Function to produce ROC-AUC curve
def fn_ROC_AUC (mdl,testX,testY):
  # probabilities from model
  model_probs = mdl.predict(testX)

  # calculate roc curves
  model_fpr, model_tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(testY, model_probs)

  # calculate the g-mean for each threshold
  gmeans = np.sqrt(model_tpr * (1-model_fpr))

  # locate the index of the largest g-mean
  ix = np.argmax(gmeans)

  print('Best Threshold=%f, G-Mean=%.3f' % (thresholds[ix], gmeans[ix]))

  #save best threshold for confusion matrix
  global best_threshold
  best_threshold = thresholds[ix]

  # calculate auc scores
  ns_auc = roc_auc_score(testY, np.zeros([2000,1]))
  model_auc = roc_auc_score(testY, model_probs)

  # summarize scores
  print('No Skill: ROC AUC=%.3f' % (ns_auc))
  print('Model: ROC AUC=%.3f' % (model_auc))

  # plot the roc curve for the model
  plt.plot([0,1], [0,1], linestyle='--', label='No Skill')
  plt.plot(model_fpr, model_tpr, marker='.', label='Model')
  plt.scatter(model_fpr[ix], model_tpr[ix], marker='o', color='black', label='Best')

  # axis labels
  plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate (FPR)')
  plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate (TPR)')

  # show the legend
  plt.legend()

  # show the plot
  plt.show()

Precision-Recall curve

  • A precision-recall curve focuses on the performance of a classifier on the positive (minority class) only
  • A line plot created for the thresholds in ascending order with recall on the x-axis and precision on the y-axis
  • A no-skill model is represented by a horizontal line with a precision that is the ratio of positive examples in the dataset
  • Perfect skill classifier has full precision and recall with a dot in the top-right corner
In [108]:
#Function to produce Precision-Recall curve
def fn_Precision_Recall(mdl,testX,testY):
  # probabilities from model
  model_probs = mdl.predict(testX)

  # calculate roc curves
  pr, rc, thresholds = precision_recall_curve(testY, model_probs)

  # calculate f-score
  fscore = (2 * pr * rc) / (pr + rc)

  # locate the index of the largest f-score
  ix = np.argmax(fscore)

  print('Best Threshold=%f, F-Score=%.3f' % (thresholds[ix], fscore[ix]))

  #save best threshold for confusion matrix
  global best_threshold
  best_threshold = thresholds[ix]
  
  # plot the precision-recall curve for the model
  no_skill = len(testY[testY==1]) / len(testY)
  plt.plot([0,1], [no_skill,no_skill], linestyle='--', label='No Skill')
  plt.plot(rc, pr, marker='.', label='Model')
  plt.scatter(rc[ix], pr[ix], marker='o', color='black', label='Best')

  # axis labels
  plt.xlabel('Recall')
  plt.ylabel('Precision')

  # show the legend
  plt.legend()

  # show the plot
  plt.show()

class_weights

  • The class 'Exited = 1 is assigned a weight of 2.45 vs 0.62 for the class 'Exited = 0' due to the imbalance between the two classes
  • This allows the model to give more importance to the minority class, which is Exited = 1 (customers who left the bank services)

Model Performance Evaluation

  • Our primary focus for this problem statement is Recall, since we should be looking to reduce false negatives.

  • False Negative in this case means this

    • Reality: A customer leaves bank services
    • Model predicted: The customer will NOT leave bank services
  • False Negative causes the bank huge loss

  • We should also keep an eye on False positives, since that causes the bank to spend more resources

  • Here is a dataframe that shows Accuracy, Precision, Recall and F1-score for all models that we created (with optimal threshold from Precision-Recall curve)

    * Random Forest basic model
* Model1 - Basic DNN
* Model2 - With early stopping and weight initialization
* Model3 - With class-weight
* Model4 - Model-1 on Oversampled data
* Model5 - Model-1 on Undersampled data

  • Model4 and Model5 are done after resampling since dataset is imbalanced

  • For Model 1,2 and 3 we have calculated accuracy,precision and recall based on default threshold (0.5) and optimal threshold from precision-recall curve

  • Example -> Model1-def is the metrics with threshold 0.5 and Model1-opt is the metrics with optimal threshold

  • More hyper-parameter tuning can be done to achive better recall, while not compromising precision much

Conclusion

As you can see here when recall is improved, precision drops a bit. We tried the following improvement steps:

1) Found out threshold using ROC-AUC, Precision-Recall

2) Done Early stopping and weight initialization

3) Appied class-weight, since this is imbalanced dataset

4) Oversampling done using SMOTE to add more samples for minority class and match it with majority class

5) Undersampling done to reduce samples for majority class and match it with minority class

There is still scope of improvements as :

1) Hyperparameter tuning can be applied to tune different Hyperparameters like learning rate etc.

We can select Model-2 as our final model based on the above analysis (giving more focus on Recall) or Model-3 if we are considering both recall and precision

Business Recommendation

  • This model can be used to predict if a customer is going to leave bank services or not, provided the feature set is going to be the same.

  • Even though the model gives more focus on false negative predictions (model predicts customer will NOT leave bank services, but customer actually leaves bank services), there is some insight towards false positive predictions (model predicts customer will leave bank services, but customer actually does NOT leave bank services) too, which in turn causes the bank extra resources.

  • Based on the analysis done by using different models, these are some of the key features bank can focus on while deciding if a customer is going to leave bank services or not

    * Geography
* Gender
* Number of Products owned by customers
* IsActiveMember
* Credit Score
* Age
* Balance (Account balance)

  • Bank can see why Exited customer % is higher for Germany

  • Bank can see why Exited customer % is higher for Females

  • Bank can see why Exited customer % is higher for customers having 3 or 4 products. This could be because the customers are not happy with these product services. Bank can focus on how to improve customer satisfaction in those areas

  • Bank can focus in active members, since they tend to keep using bank services

  • Customers with lower credit score seem to be leaving bank services more, this could be because bank is offering more services to those who are having high credit scores

  • Bank can see why Exited customer % is higher for older customers, bank can think of ways to keep them, like giving them additional benefits or offers

  • Bank can provide some benefits or offers to female customers to keep them

  • Bank can provide some benefits or offers to customers from Germany to reduce Exit %.
